==Awards==
Since 1995, ''[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]'' has ranked Adobe as an outstanding place to work. Adobe was rated the fifth-best U.S. company to work for in 2003, sixth in 2004, 31st in 2007, 40th in 2008, and eleventh in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/fortune/bestcompanies/2009/full_list/|title=100 Best Companies to Work For 2009|publisher=CNN}}</ref>
In May 2008, Adobe Systems India was ranked 19th of great places to work in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greatplacetowork.com/best/list-in.htm|title=Best Places to work in India}}</ref>  In October 2008, Adobe Systems Canada Inc. was named one of "[[Canada's Top 100 Employers]]" by Mediacorp Canada Inc., and was featured in ''[[Maclean's]]'' newsmagazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eluta.ca/top-employer-adobe-systems-canada|title=Reasons for Selection, 2009 Canada's Top 100 Employers Competition}}</ref>

==Criticism==

===Pricing===
Adobe has been criticized for its pricing practices,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.zdnet.co.uk/software/0,1000000121,39497760,00.htm?r=1|title=Adobe responds to CS4 pricing criticism}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.builderau.com.au/news/soa/Adobe-defends-CS4-pricing/0,339028227,339292472,00.htm|title=Adobe defends CS4 pricing}}</ref> with retail prices being as much as twice as high in non-US countries as in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.creativepro.com/article/creative-suite-pricing-varies-throughout-world|title=Adobe responds to customer protests against perceived unfair pricing.}}</ref> As pointed out by many, it is significantly cheaper to pay for a return airfare ticket to the United States and purchase one particular collection of Adobe's software there than to buy it locally in Australia.<ref>[http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2013/02/dont-believe-the-adobe-price-cut-hype-its-still-gauging-you-silly/ Don’t Believe The Adobe Price Cut Hype, It’s Still Gouging You Silly], Gizmodo</ref><ref>[http://www.theage.com.au/technology/technology-news/adobe-has-its-head-in-the-clouds-over-pricing-20130215-2ehat.html Adobe has its head in the clouds over pricing], The Age - Technology</ref>

After Adobe revealed the pricing for the Creative Suite 3 Master Collection, which was £1,000 higher for European customers,<ref>[http://www.zdnet.com/uk-will-pay-1000-more-for-adobe-cs3-3039286561/ UK will pay £1,000 more for Adobe CS3 | ZDNet]</ref> a petition to protest over "unfair pricing" was published and signed by 10,000 users.<ref>[http://photo.net/photography-news-forum/00LDbS 10,000 sign Adobe CS3 European pricing petition | Photo.net]</ref> In June 2009, Adobe further increased its prices in the UK by 10% in spite of weakening of the pound against the dollar,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pcpro.co.uk/news/254173/adobe-hikes-uk-prices-by-10.html|title=Adobe hikes UK prices by 10% &#124; News|publisher=PC Pro|date=June 1, 2009|accessdate=May 29, 2010}}</ref> and UK users are not allowed to buy from the US store.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/technology/2009/jun/04/adobe-software Adobe widens the price gap | The Guardian]</ref>

In 2011, after the company announced that it will only allow owners of the most recent versions of [[Creative Suite]] to upgrade to new versions, [[Scott Kelby]], The President of The [[National Association of Photoshop Professionals]], wrote an open letter to Adobe requesting it re-thinks its product upgrade policy.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/2011/11/22/AdobeUpgradeCriticism Adobe faces criticism for change of upgrade policy | Digital Photography Review]</ref><ref>[http://scottkelby.com/2011/an-open-letter-to-adobe-systems/ An Open Letter To Adobe Systems | Scott Kelby's Photoshop Insider]</ref>

===Customer service===
The company has been criticized by users for bad customer service.<ref>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/australian-it-old/adobe-delays-anger-users/story-e6frgamo-1225765761841 Adobe delays anger users | The Australian]</ref> In August 2009 Adobe apologized on their main support web page for poor customer service.<ref>[http://www.creativepro.com/article/adobe-apologizes-world-poor-customer-service, Adobe Apologizes to World for Poor Customer Service | CreativePro]</ref><ref>[http://www.macworld.co.uk/mac-creative/news/?newsid=27049 Adobe repairing broken customer services | MacWorld UK]</ref>

===Security===
For years hackers have exploited vulnerabilities in Adobe programs, such as Adobe Reader, to gain unauthorized access to computers.<ref>[http://money.cnn.com/2013/10/08/technology/security/adobe-security/ Adobe has an epically abysmal security record - CNNMoney]</ref> Adobe's Flash Player has also been criticized for, among other things, suffering from performance, memory usage and security problems (see [[Flash player#Criticism|criticism of Flash Player]]). A report by security researchers from [[Kaspersky Lab]] criticized Adobe for producing the products having top 10 security vulnerabilities.<ref>[http://windowsitpro.com/blog/adobe-fares-poorly-kaspersky-lab-security-report Adobe Fares Poorly in Kaspersky Lab Security Report | WindowsITPro]</ref>

Observers noted that Adobe was spying on its customers by including [[spyware]] in the Creative Suite 3 software and quietly sending user data to a firm named [[Omniture]].<ref>[http://www.techdirt.com/articles/20071228/020818.shtml Adobe Spying On Its Customers | Techdirt]</ref> When users became aware, Adobe explained what the suspicious software did and admitted that they "could and should do a better job taking security concerns into account".<ref>[http://blogs.adobe.com/jnack/2007/12/adobe_ate_me_baby.html John Nack on Adobe: Adobe ate me baby!!]</ref> When a security flaw was later discovered in Photoshop CS5, Adobe sparked outrage by saying it would leave the flaw unpatched, so anyone who wanted to use the software securely would have to pay for an upgrade.<ref>[http://www.techweekeurope.co.uk/news/adobe-creative-suite-patch-backtrac-77760 Adobe Backtracks On Patching ‘PR Disaster’ | TechWeekEurope]</ref> Following a fierce backlash Adobe decided to provide the software patch.<ref>[http://blogs.csoonline.com/data-protection/2178/was-stupid-adobe That was stupid, Adobe | CSO Blogs]</ref>

===Marketing ethics===
Adobe has been criticized for pushing [[foistware]] - third-party browser toolbars and free virus scanners, usually as part of the [[Adobe Flash|Flash]] update process,<ref>[http://www.zdnet.com/blog/bott/adobe-and-skype-top-my-foistware-hall-of-shame/3195 Adobe and Skype top my Foistware Hall of Shame | ZDNet]</ref> and for pushing a third-party [[scareware]] program designed to scare users into paying for unneeded system repairs.<ref>[http://www.zdnet.com/blog/bott/adobes-latest-critical-security-update-pushes-scareware/4681 Adobe's latest critical security update pushes scareware | ZDNet]</ref>

===Criticism of Creative Cloud===
{{main|Adobe Creative Cloud}}
Adobe has caused concerns within the photography and filmmaking community, especially long term users.<ref>[http://castroller.com/podcasts/LensworkPhotography/3569325 The Real Lesson in the Adobe Announcement | Lenswork Daily]</ref><ref>[http://www.graphics.com/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=1047 The Creative Cloud Chronicles: Adobe is Not Microsoft | Graphics.com]</ref> In May 2013, Adobe Systems announced plans to end perpetual software licensing for its [[Adobe Creative Suite|Creative Suite]] products in favor of a subscription-based service model called Creative Cloud, which had been introduced as an alternative licensing model in May 2012.

Shifting to a [[software as a service]] model, Adobe announced more frequent feature updates to its products and the eschewing of their traditional [[release cycle]]s.<ref>Summers, Nick. (2013-05-06) [http://thenextweb.com/insider/2013/05/06/after-nearly-10-years-adobe-abandons-its-creative-suite-entirely-to-focus-on-creative-cloud/ Adobe Abandons Its Creative Suite to Focus on Creative Cloud]. Thenextweb.com. Retrieved on 2013-07-21.</ref> Customers must pay a monthly subscription fee and if they stop paying, they will lose access to the software as well as to the work they saved in [[proprietary format|proprietary file format]],<ref>[http://www.columbian.com/news/2013/jun/02/adobe-casts-cloud-on-budgets/ Adobe casts cloud on budgets | The Columbian]</ref> which is not [[backward-compatible]] with the Creative Suite<ref>[http://blog.phischeye.de/2013/05/08/open-letter-to-adobe-about-the-creative-cloud-subscription-model/ Open Letter to Adobe about the Creative Cloud Subscription Model]</ref><ref name="tidbits">[http://tidbits.com/article/13765 | Creative Cloud Complaints Darken Adobe’s View of the Future | TidBITS]</ref> (Adobe admitted that this is a valid concern<ref>[http://blogs.adobe.com/jnack/2013/05/you-should-never-lose-access-to-your-work-period.html John Nack on Adobe: You should never lose access to your work, period.]</ref>). In addition, they will not be able to retrieve their files from the cloud once the subscription has expired.<ref>[http://www.geekwire.com/2013/adobe-ceo-extols-virtues-creative-cloud/ Adobe says shift to Creative Cloud subscriptions is working, despite controversy]</ref> They must have Internet connection<ref>[http://photographylife.com/adobe-creative-cloud-fail Adobe Creative Cloud Fail | Photographylife.com]</ref> to download the software and to use the 2 GB of provided storage space (or the additionally purchased 20 GB<ref>[http://www.luminous-landscape.com/essays/adobe_cc.shtml Clouding The Issue | The Luminous Landscape]</ref>), and must validate the license monthly.<ref name="captive">[http://www.keptlight.com/2013/05/creative-cloud-or-captive-consumer/ Creative Cloud or Captive Consumer]</ref>

Although investors applauded the move, the reaction across segments of Adobe’s user base was swift and apocalyptic.<ref>[http://www.forbes.com/sites/amadoudiallo/2013/06/17/adobe-cc-subscription-release-big-upside-and-risk/ Adobe's Subscription-Only CC Release Carries Obvious Upside But Big Risk | Forbes]</ref> This shift has been met with mixed reviews by both corporations and independent designers, with many people expressing their displeasure on the web<ref>[http://venturebeat.com/2013/05/11/adobe-creative-cloud-interview/ Adobe exec: Creative Cloud complainers will love us once they try us (interview)], VentureBeat</ref><ref>[http://mashable.com/2013/05/13/adobe-creative-cloud-top-comments/ Adobe's Move to the Cloud Incites Anger and Other Top Comments], Mashable</ref><ref>[http://www.macworld.co.uk/digitallifestyle/news/?newsid=3446802  Adobe Creative Cloud: Reactions, responses and reassurance | Macworld UK]</ref> and through multiple [[internet petitions]]<ref>Neil Bennett (15 May 2013) [http://www.digitalartsonline.co.uk/news/creative-software/analysis-real-reason-adobe-ditched-creative-suite-for-creative-cloud/ Analysis: The real reason Adobe ditched Creative Suite for Creative Cloud], Retrieved on 2013-07-21, www.digitalartsonline.co.uk</ref> calling upon Adobe to continue selling creative software under the perpetual licensing model.<ref>[http://www.truth-out.org/speakout/item/16442-adobes-creative-cloud-sparks-thunderous-revolt Adobe’s Creative Cloud Sparks Thunderous Revolt],  25 May 2013, truth-out.org</ref> Among these was a [[Change.org]] petition which reached over 30,000 signatures within a few weeks of the announcement. Currently at 44,000.<ref>[http://www.foxbusiness.com/technology/2013/05/17/some-artists-give-adobe-cloud-switch-critical-review/ Some Artists Give Adobe's Cloud Switch a Critical Review], Fox Business</ref>

According to the critics, the move to a perpetual rental scheme was highly disruptive to many users,<ref>[http://www.clearpointe.com/why-adobe-is-making-a-big-mistake-in-going-cloud-only/ Why Adobe Is Making A Big Mistake In Going Cloud-Only | ClearPointe]</ref> and caused an unprecedented loss of trust in Adobe as a company and an attendant rise in anxiety among their customers.<ref>[http://www.graphics.com/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=1044 The Creative Cloud Chronicles: Freeing the Captive Consumer], Graphics.com</ref><ref>[http://www.pcpro.co.uk/blogs/2013/05/10/why-i-wont-subscribe-to-creative-cloud/ Why I won’t subscribe to Creative Cloud | PC Pro blog]</ref> Users noted that they have not always wanted, nor could they afford, to upgrade to the newest versions of the software, and the new licensing was essentially forcing them to do this.<ref>[http://thephotovideoguy.ca/?tag=boycott-adobe-creative-cloud Why Adobe Creative Cloud is a bad idea for photographers | The Photo Video Guy]</ref> College officials expressed their concern with the new licensing terms, worried about rising costs and have asked about switching to alternative products.<ref>[http://www.insidehighered.com/news/2013/05/22/adobe-pricing-plan-raises-concerns Confusion in the Cloud | Inside Higher Ed]</ref>

Adobe [[VP]] of Creative Solutions responded that they "expected a higher degree of this type of reaction from the hobbyist photographic community".<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/news/2013/05/08/Adobe-photoshop-cc Photoshop CC: Adobe responds to reaction | Digital Photography Review]</ref> Despite a storm of customer criticism over Adobe's move to subscription-only pricing,<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1001_3-57586616-92/as-adobe-customers-howl-corel-offers-education-discount/ As Adobe customers howl, Corel offers education discount |  Business Tech - CNET News]</ref> the company announced that it would not sell perpetual licenses to its software alongside the subscriptions - "We understand this is a big change, but we are so focused on the vision we shared for Creative Cloud, and we plan to focus all our new innovation on the Creative Cloud".<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1001_3-57586521-92/dislike-adobes-creative-cloud-subscriptions-tough-beans/ Dislike Adobe's Creative Cloud subscriptions? Tough beans | Business Tech - CNET News]</ref>

[[Digital Photography Review]] wrote that the new license scheme  increased [[Fear, uncertainty and doubt|fear, uncertainty, doubt]], expense and risk. The website suggested that serious photographers reestablish a trusted and "Good Photography Workflow" without monthly payments for the next 10 years.<ref>[http://www.dpreview.com/articles/3167814967/rfc-beating-photoshops-rent-forever-cloud-trap/2 RFC: Beating Photoshop's Rent Forever Cloud Trap | Digital Photography Review]</ref> Online articles began offering examples of replacements of Photoshop,<ref>[http://www.pcmag.com/article2/0,2817,2418674,00.asp 7 Adobe Photoshop CC Alternatives | PCMag.com]</ref><ref>[http://www.webdesignerdepot.com/2013/06/15-alternatives-to-adobe-creative-cloud/ 15+ alternatives to Adobe Creative Cloud | Webdesigner Depot]</ref> Illustrator, and other programs,<ref>[http://lifehacker.com/5976725/build-your-own-adobe-creative-suite-with-free-and-cheap-software Build Your Own Adobe Creative Suite with Free and Cheap Software]</ref><ref>[http://www.extremetech.com/computing/155285-bring-out-the-gimp-adobe-photoshop-and-creative-suite-to-become-subscription-only Bring out the GIMP: Adobe Photoshop and Creative Suite to become subscription-only], ExtremeTech</ref><ref>[http://www.macworld.co.uk/mac-creative/news/?newsid=3452957 Alternatives to Adobe's Creative Cloud | Macworld UK]</ref> with competing products such as [[CorelDRAW]],<ref>[http://coreldraw.com/blogs/gerard/archive/2013/03/26/coreldraw-subscription-or-perpetual-box-download-it-s-your-choice.aspx CorelDRAW Subscription or Perpetual Box / Download – It’s Your Choice, CorelDRAW.com]</ref> [[PaintShop Pro]],<ref>[http://www.imaging-resource.com/news/2013/05/20/corel-woos-customers-unhappy-adobe-subscription-only-creative-cloud-planCorel woos customers unhappy with Adobe’s subscription-only Creative Cloud plan], Imaging Resource</ref> and [[Pixelmator]]<ref>[http://www.pixelmator.com/blog/2013/05/07/cloudiness/ Cloudiness | Pixelmator Blog]</ref> directly offering alternatives, and launching promotions for dissatisfied Adobe customers.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1001_3-57589309-92/adobe-competitors-pounce-after-subscription-backlash/ Adobe competitors pounce after subscription backlash | Business Tech - CNET News]</ref> [[David Hobby]], the author of Strobist.com, [[Tweet (Twitter)|tweeted]]: "I like Photoshop; I still use CS3. But I am *not* renting PS for $600/yr. Period. Big winner: [[Capture One]], which now needs a LR clone."<ref>[https://twitter.com/strobist/status/331467821722791936 David Hobby (@strobist) on the Creative Cloud | Twitter.com]</ref>

Adobe, however, claimed that Creative Cloud is its "highest customer satisfaction product in the creative space" and that even prior to Adobe's move to a pure subscription model, "more than 80 percent of customers who bought products from Adobe's Web site picked CC over CS." <ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1001_3-57586521-92/dislike-adobes-creative-cloud-subscriptions-tough-beans/ Dislike Adobe's Creative Cloud subscriptions? Tough beans | CNET News]</ref>

Creative Cloud has been criticized for broken file syncing, one of its core features.<ref name="syncing">[http://www.theregister.co.uk/2013/05/17/adobe_creative_cloud_problem/ Adobe's Creative Cloud fails at being a cloud | The Register]</ref><ref>[http://geeks.broadwayworld.com/article/Adobe-Creative-Cloud-FAIL-Suspends-File-Sync-Service-20130519 Adobe Creative Cloud FAIL; Suspends File Sync Service | BWWGeeksWorld]</ref> In May 2013 Adobe announced that it was suspending the file-sync desktop preview "for the next couple of weeks".<ref name="syncing" /> Reviewers of Creative Cloud were disappointed with the functionality of the [[cloud storage]]<ref>[http://www.macworld.co.uk/mac-creative/reviews/?reviewid=3375113 Adobe Creative Cloud review | MacWorld UK]</ref><ref>[http://www.blurmediaphotography.com/adobe-creative-cloud-review/ Adobe Creative Cloud Review | blurMEDIA]</ref><ref>[http://www.maclife.com/article/reviews/adobe_creative_cloud_review Adobe Creative Cloud Review | Mac|Life]</ref> and were "far from convinced by Adobe's subscription model".<ref>[http://www.pcpro.co.uk/reviews/software/382786/adobe-creative-cloud Adobe Creative Cloud review | PC Pro]</ref> Users were concerned that they would be forced to upgrade their computer hardware when it is no longer supported by the current version of the Creative Cloud software.<ref>[http://blog.dvfanatics.com/2013/06/my-problem-with-adobe-creative-cloud.html My Problem with Adobe Creative Cloud | DVFanatics]</ref>

Although Creative Cloud was expected to end the [[software piracy|piracy]] of [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]],<ref>[http://gizmodo.com/will-adobes-move-to-the-cloud-finally-keep-the-pirates-493172511 Will Adobe's Move to the Cloud Finally Keep the Pirates at Bay? | Gizmodo]</ref> which is one of the most pirated pieces of software,<ref>[http://www.theverge.com/2013/6/20/4447916/adobe-photoshop-cc-pirated-in-one-day Adobe's subscription-only Photoshop CC has already been pirated | The Verge]</ref> Creative Cloud was hacked and its applications made illegally available a day after it officially launched.<ref>[http://news.cnet.com/8301-1009_3-57590213-83/that-was-quick-adobes-creative-cloud-already-pirated/ That was quick: Adobe's Creative Cloud already pirated | CNET News]</ref><ref>[http://www.technobuffalo.com/2013/06/21/photoshop-cc-already-cracked-in-the-first-day/ Cracked With a Vengeance: Photoshop CC Pirated In One Day | TechnoBuffalo]</ref> However, Adobe claims that Creative Cloud will be more accessible and provide better value – “We believe in fighting piracy of software by making the right software for the right people at the right price”.<ref>[https://torrentfreak.com/adobe-photoshop-pirates-arent-bad-people-who-like-to-steal-things-130509/ Adobe: Photoshop Pirates Aren’t Bad People Who Like to Steal Things | TorrentFreak]</ref>

The service has been criticized for its price, which is higher in Europe than in the US and according to Adobe is based on "customer research that assesses the value of the product in the local market".<ref>[http://forums.adobe.com/message/4372666 Adobe Community: Why Creative Cloud for Europe is so expensive? (Adobe Staff response)]</ref> Critics noted that Adobe lists 29 supported currencies, whereas boxed versions could be installed in any of the world’s 249 territories without issue.<ref>[http://www.extremetech.com/computing/155285-bring-out-the-gimp-adobe-photoshop-and-creative-suite-to-become-subscription-only Bring out the GIMP: Adobe Photoshop and Creative Suite to become subscription-only]</ref> Current users of Creative Suite 3 and higher get discounts for the Creative Cloud service for a limited time, after which the subscription cost increases.<ref name="captive">[http://www.keptlight.com/2013/05/creative-cloud-or-captive-consumer/ Creative Cloud or Captive Consumer]</ref>

Creative Cloud has also been criticized for its [[Terms of Use]], a license agreement that according to the critics raises issues with [[Internet privacy|privacy]], predictability and fairness for the customer.<ref>[http://macperformanceguide.com/blog/2013/20130508_1-Adobe-birth-date.html Adobe Creative Cloud: Date of Birth Mandatory, Lopsided Legal Agreement | Mac Performance Guide]</ref><ref>[http://macperformanceguide.com/blog/2013/20130508_1a-Adobe-legal-agreement.html Adobe Creative Cloud: Lopsided Legal Agreement | Mac Performance Guide]</ref><ref>[http://www.graphics.com/modules.php?name=Sections&op=viewarticle&artid=1046 The Creative Cloud Chronicles: The Chilling Wind of Big Brother | Graphics.com]</ref> Users worried about the [[Cloud computing security|security]] implications of putting their assets to the cloud.<ref>[http://www.studiodaily.com/2013/05/adobe-doubles-down-on-creative-cloud-adopts-subscription-only-software-model/ Adobe Doubles Down on Creative Cloud, Adopts Subscription-Only Model | Studio Daily]</ref>

===Source code and customer data breach===

On October 3, 2013, the company initially revealed that 2.9 million customers' sensitive and personal data was stolen in security breach which included encrypted credit card information.<ref>[http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24392819 BBC]</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Adobe accounts hacked, data exposed for 2.9 million customers - Digital Photography Review|url=http://www.dpreview.com/news/2013/10/03/adobe-accounts-hacked-data-exposed-for-2-9-million-customers?ref=related-news}}</ref><ref>http://news.cnet.com/8301-1009_3-57605962-83/adobe-hacked-3-million-accounts-compromised/ Adobe hacked, 3 million accounts compromised | Security & Privacy - CNET News</ref> Adobe later admitted that 38 million active users have been affected and the attackers obtained access to their IDs and encrypted passwords, as well as to many inactive Adobe accounts.<ref>http://news.cnet.com/8301-1009_3-57609753-83/adobe-hack-attack-affected-38-million-accounts/ Adobe hack attack affected 38 million accounts | Security & Privacy - CNET News</ref><ref>[http://krebsonsecurity.com/2013/10/adobe-breach-impacted-at-least-38-million-users/ Adobe Breach Impacted At Least 38 Million Users — Krebs on Security]</ref><ref>http://www.zdnet.com/adobe-security-breach-actually-affected-closer-to-38-million-users-7000022560/ Adobe security breach actually affected closer to 38 million users | ZDNet</ref> The company did not make it clear if all the personal information was encrypted, such as email addresses and physical addresses, though data privacy laws in 44 states require this information to be encrypted.<ref>[http://en.kioskea.net/news/24146-adobe-cyber-attack-was-a-lesson-for-corporations Adobe Cyber Attack was a Lesson for Corporations - Kioskea.net]</ref><ref>[http://www.forbes.com/sites/alexkonrad/2013/10/09/how-safe-is-encrypted-card-data-adobe/ After Security Breach Exposes 2.9 Million Adobe Users, How Safe Is Encrypted Credit Card Data? - Forbes]</ref>

A 3.8 GB file stolen from Adobe and containing 152 million usernames, reversibly encrypted passwords and unencrypted password hints was posted on AnonNews.org.<ref>http://arstechnica.com/security/2013/11/how-an-epic-blunder-by-adobe-could-strengthen-hand-of-password-crackers/ How an epic blunder by Adobe could strengthen hand of password crackers | Ars Technica</ref><ref>[http://www.the-digital-reader.com/2013/10/29/adobe-hack-much-worse-previosuly-reported-38-million-accounts-affected/ Adobe Hack Was Much Worse than Previosuly Reported - 38 Million Accounts Affected - The Digital Reader]</ref> [[LastPass]], a password security firm, said that Adobe failed to use best practices for securing the passwords and has not [[Salt (cryptography)|salted]] them<ref>http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/11/07/us-adobe-cyberattack-idUKBRE9A61D220131107 Trove of Adobe user data found on Web after breach: security firm | Reuters</ref><ref>[http://www.csoonline.com/article/742570/adobe-confirms-stolen-passwords-were-encrypted-not-hashed Adobe confirms stolen passwords were encrypted, not hashed - CSO Online - Security and Risk]</ref> Another security firm, [[Sophos]], showed that Adobe used a weak encryption method allowing to recover a lot of information with very little effort.<ref>[http://www.bit-tech.net/news/bits/2013/11/05/adobe-breach-2/1 Adobe data breach far worse than first claimed | bit-tech.net]</ref><ref>[http://nakedsecurity.sophos.com/2013/11/04/anatomy-of-a-password-disaster-adobes-giant-sized-cryptographic-blunder/ Anatomy of a password disaster – Adobe’s giant-sized cryptographic blunder | Naked Security]</ref> [[Facebook]] and [[Evernote]] began notifying their users who used the same email addresses for their accounts as those compromised in the Adobe breach.<ref>[http://krebsonsecurity.com/2013/11/facebook-warns-users-after-adobe-breach/ Facebook Warns Users After Adobe Breach — Krebs on Security]</ref><ref>[http://www.tripwire.com/state-of-security/top-security-stories/evernote-warns-vulnerable-users-wake-adobe-breach/ Evernote Warns Vulnerable Users in Wake of Adobe Breach | The State of Security]</ref> According to an [[IT]] expert, Adobe has failed its customers and ‘should hang their heads in shame’.<ref>[http://business-technology.co.uk/2013/11/adobe-should-hang-their-heads-in-shame-following-cyber-attack/ Adobe 'should hang their heads in shame' following cyber attack - Business Technology]</ref>

Many of the credit cards were tied to the [[Creative Cloud]] software-by-subscription service.<ref>http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9243010/Adobe_hack_shows_subscription_software_vendors_lucrative_targets?pageNumber=1 Adobe hack shows subscription software vendors lucrative targets | Computerworld</ref> Adobe offered its affected US customers a free membership in a credit monitoring service, but no similar arrangements have been made for non-US customers.<ref>http://www.lifehacker.com.au/2013/10/massive-adobe-security-breach-change-your-passwords-now/ Massive Adobe Security Breach: Change Your Passwords Now | Lifehacker Australia</ref><ref>http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2013/10/adobe-treating-australians-as-lesser-beings-even-after-details-of-2-9-million-accounts-were-stolen/ Adobe Treating Australians As Lesser Beings Even After Details Of 2.9 Million Accounts Were Stolen | Gizmodo Australia</ref> When a [[data breach]] occurs in the US, penalties depend on the state where the victim resides, not where the company is based.<ref>http://www.cruxialcio.com/get-smart-state-statutes-after-adobes-data-breach-2065 Get Smart on State Statutes After Adobe’s Data Breach | Cruxialcio</ref> Ten weeks after the attack was discovered Adobe said that it was taking longer than expected to warn customers about the massive data breach, leaving some in the dark.<ref>[http://uk.reuters.com/article/2013/11/25/us-adobe-cyberattack-idUKBRE9AO10R20131125 Adobe says breach notification taking longer than anticipated | Reuters]</ref>

A [[class-action lawsuit]] has been filed against Adobe for failing to safeguard the login credentials and financial information of consumers who used Adobe’s [[Creative Cloud]] service<ref name="topclassactions5417">[http://www.topclassactions.com/lawsuit-settlements/lawsuit-news/5417-massive-adobe-data-breach-leads-to-class-action-lawsuit Massive Adobe Data Breach Leads to Class Action Lawsuit | Top Class Actions]</ref><ref>[http://www.databreaches.net/adobe-customer-files-potential-class-action-lawsuit-after-breach/ Adobe customer files potential class action lawsuit after breach | databreaches.net]</ref> - "In this case it is alleged that Adobe requires many of its consumers to keep active credit and debit card numbers on file but did not safeguard them from hackers".<ref>[http://www.girardgibbs.com/blog/girard-gibbs-files-class-action-lawsuit-against-adobe/ Girard Gibbs Files Class Action Lawsuit Against Adobe Systems, Inc. | Girard Gibbs LLP]</ref> Experts cited in the lawsuit claim there will be future breaches by hackers resulting from Adobe's "shoddy security protocols" and reliance on a "software-as-a-service" system.<ref name="topclassactions5417"></ref>

After stealing the customers' data, cyber-thieves also accessed Adobe's [[source code]] repository, likely in mid-August 2013.<ref>http://www.infoworld.com/t/application-security/adobe-fesses-hack-fudges-details-228189 Adobe fesses up to hack but fudges on details | Application security - InfoWorld</ref> Because [[Hacker (computer security)|hackers]] acquired copies of the source code of Adobe [[proprietary software|proprietary]] products,<ref>http://www.smh.com.au/it-pro/security-it/adobe-hacked-customer-data-source-code-compromised-20131004-hv1wl.html Adobe hacked: customer data, source code compromised | The Sydney Morning Herald</ref><ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/10/04/adobe-hacked_n_4042351.html BBC Adobe Hacked: Cyber-Thieves Accessed Credit Card Information Of Nearly 3 Million Customers]</ref> they could find and exploit any potential weaknesses in its security, computer experts warned.<ref>http://www.nytimes.com/2013/10/04/technology/adobe-announces-security-breach.html?_r=0 Adobe Announces Security Breach | The New York Times</ref> Security researcher Alex Holden, chief information security officer of Hold Security, characterized this Adobe breach, which affected [[Adobe Acrobat|Acrobat]], [[ColdFusion]] and numerous other applications, as "one of the worst in US history".<ref>[http://gigaom.com/2013/10/07/ruh-roh-adobe-breach-is-just-the-beginning-researcher-says/ Ruh-roh: Adobe breach is just the beginning, researcher says]</ref> Adobe also announced that hackers stole parts of the source code of [[Photoshop]], which according to commentators could allow programmers to copy its engineering techniques<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-24740873 BBC News - Adobe hack: At least 38 million accounts breached</ref> and would make it easier to pirate Adobe's expensive products.<ref>[http://www.huffingtonpost.com/adam-levin/why-the-adobe-hack-scares_b_4277064.html Why the Adobe Hack Scares Me - And Why It Should Scare You | Adam Levin]</ref>

According to Hold Security, a firm which discovered 40 GB of Adobe's source code<ref>http://krebsonsecurity.com/2013/10/adobe-to-announce-source-code-customer-data-breach/ | Adobe To Announce Source Code, Customer Data Breach — Krebs on Security</ref>  on a server of a Russian-speaking [[hacker group]],<ref>http://www.pcworld.com/article/2054160/adobes-source-code-was-parked-on-hackers-unprotected-server.html Adobe's source code was parked on hackers' unprotected server | PCWorld</ref> the "disclosure of encryption algorithms, other security schemes, and software vulnerabilities can be used to bypass protections for individual and corporate data" and may have opened the gateway to new generation [[zero-day attack]]s.<ref>http://www.holdsecurity.com/?_escaped_fragment_=news2013/c13i1#!news2013/c13i1 Hold Security, LLC discovers hackers stealing source code for Adobe flagship products | Hold Security</ref> Hackers already used ColdFusion exploits to make off with usernames and encrypted passwords of [[PR Newswire]]'s customers, which has been tied to the Adobe security breach.<ref>[http://krebsonsecurity.com/2013/10/breach-at-pr-newswire-tied-to-adobe-hack/ Breach at PR Newswire Tied to Adobe Hack — Krebs on Security]</ref><ref>[http://gigaom.com/2013/10/17/adobe-code-theft-raises-its-ugly-head-in-pr-newswire-breach/ Adobe code theft raises its ugly head in PR Newswire breach — Tech News and Analysis]</ref> They also used a ColdFusion exploit to breach Washington state court and expose up to 160,000 Social Security numbers.<ref>http://www.zdnet.com/hackers-breached-washington-state-court-with-adobe-coldfusion-flaw-7000015199/ Hackers breached Washington state court with Adobe ColdFusion flaw | ZDNet</ref>

